BILL_SESSION_CONTEXT: client_id={{1.`2`}}; session_id={{1.`6`}}

KEYS & EXPLAINERS

Sets Reps Load
This tells you how many sets to perform, how many reps per set, and the suggested weight (load) to use. Example: 3 10 @ 40kg means 3 sets, 10 reps per set, with roughly 40kg.

RPE (Rate of Perceived Exertion)
RPE estimates how hard a set should feel.
14: Very easy warm-up
56: Comfortable working effort
78: Challenging but repeatable
9: Near limit
10: Max effort stop before this unless instructed

Tempo Codes
Tempo is written as 4 numbers: Eccentric Bottom Pause Concentric Top Pause.
Examples:
3-0-1-0: 3 seconds down, no pause, 1 second up, no pause.
2-1-2-0: 2 seconds down, 1 second pause, 2 seconds up.
X-0-1-0: X means explosive move up as fast as you can with control.

Pattern Types
These describe how loads change across sets:
Flat: Same weight every set.
Ramp to Target: Weight increases each set until the top set.
Top Set + Back-offs: One heavy set, then lighter sets.
Reverse Pyramid: Heavy first set, lighter sets after.
Intervals: Work/rest pattern for cardio.

Target Level
This indicates the intended intensity (effort) or load progression for the exercise. Bill uses this along with RPE and tempo to guide the training stimulus.

Rest
Use whatever rest you need to hit good reps with good form. A typical guideline: 13 minutes for strength/hypertrophy sets; 3060 seconds for accessories.

Warm-up Guidance
Start each session by moving through the joints and muscles used in the main lifts. Begin with light versions of each movement before loading up the first working set.

Cool-down Guidance
Move lightly after training gentle stretching, breathing, or walking for a few minutes helps reduce stiffness.

Safety Notes
If you feel sharp pain, numbness, instability, or anything that feels wrong, stop the set immediately and make a quick note for Bill.

All right then, lets have a good one tomorrow.

Bill

Quick Reference

RPE (Rate of Perceived Exertion): Aim for the effort target for each set. RPE 78 = solid working sets; leave 12 good reps in the tank.

Tempo: Follow the tempo shown (e.g., 3-0-1-0). Slower down-phase, controlled up-phase unless X is shown for explosive intent.

Patterns: Pattern names describe how load progresses across sets. Common ones:
Flat same load each set
Ramp build up to the heaviest set
Top + Backoff one heavy set, lighter sets after
Reverse Pyramid hardest first, then lighter sets

Adjustments: If load feels off on the day, adjust so the target RPE is met while maintaining good form.
